{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bd1d3db5-c84c-4c0c-ad62-9323ef34fa12","content":"## What Changed\n\nC# 14 introduced **first-class span support**, which adds an implicit conversion from `T[]` to `ReadOnlySpan<T>` in more contexts — including extension method resolution. This means `array.Contains(num)` now resolves to:\n\n```\nMemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<int>, int)   // ← C# 14 picks this\n```\n\ninstead of the previous:\n\n```\nEnumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)      // ← C# 13 picked this\n```\n\n`ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct** and ref structs cannot be captured in expression trees — so the expression tree either fails to compile or produces a node the interpreter cannot execute at runtime.\n\n## How to Fix\n\nDisambiguate by steering overload resolution back to the `IEnumerable<T>` overload. Either approach works:\n\n**Option A — Cast the array:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\n**Option B — Call `Enumerable.Contains` explicitly:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nBoth force the compiler to bind to the `Enumerable` overload, which uses `IEnumerable<T>` (not a ref struct) and is fully representable in expression trees.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5453676e-5787-4c99-bd5f-beac71db23df","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 related to LINQ expression trees and the `.Contains()` method on arrays.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to how extension methods work. C# 14 introduces **extension members** (a new feature), but more relevantly, there's a change in how the compiler resolves `Contains` on arrays.\n\nThe key issue: In earlier versions of C#, when you called `array.Contains(num)` wher