pan<T>`, this breaks the compilation or execution of the expression tree.\n\nWhether this manifests as a compile error or runtime error depends on the exact implementation, though it should be a compile error when a lambda is directly assigned to `Expression<Func<...>>`. The underlying issue and fix remain the same regardless. The compiler performs overload resolution when lowering the lambda to an expression tree, and if it picks `MemoryExtensions.Contains`, that's where the problem originates.\n\nSo I should explain that C# 14's first-class span support changed how `array.Contains(x)` resolves, causing it to bind to the `MemoryExtensions` overload with `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, which can't be represented in expression trees.\n\nI'm overthinking this. Let me just provide the clear answer about what changed and why it breaks.","outputTokens":3829,"requestId":"284F:2CF44:ACCC85:C9364F:69EABD86"},"id":"b3e768e4-ddb7-4d81-92a9-816b5083e9fd","timestamp":"2026-04-24T00:48:16.278Z","parentId":"a6c8df9b-8afb-4660-b384-e1ca80993719"}
